"obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.7975274324417114, "span": {"begin": 1224, "end": 1228}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "R249S", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.6740038394927979, "span": {"begin": 1234, "end": 1239}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "R249S", "mutationType": "ProteinMutation", "normalizedName": "p|SUB|R|249|S;RS#:28934571", "obj": "mutation", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1234, "end": 1239}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "patients", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9777877330780029, "span": {"begin": 1261, "end": 1269}}, {"id": ["mim:114550", "mesh:D006528"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "HCC", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9998433589935303, "span": {"begin": 1325, "end": 1328}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "plasma", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.5451028943061829, "span": {"begin": 1363, "end": 1369}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "codon 249 p53", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.7396950125694275, "span": {"begin": 1388, "end": 1401}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:100133255"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "codon 249 p53 mutation", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9975564479827881, "span": {"begin": 1388, "end": 1410}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009369"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "tumors", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.999997615814209, "span": {"begin": 1418, "end": 1424}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "patients", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9929428696632385, "span": {"begin": 1439, "end": 1447}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "R249S", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.587150514125824, "span": {"begin": 1611, "end": 1616}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "R249S", "mutationType": "ProteinMutation", "normalizedName": "p|SUB|R|249|S;RS#:28934571", "obj": "mutation", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1611, "end": 1616}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "plasma", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.433564156293869, "span": {"begin": 1633, "end": 1639}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "patients", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9740047454833984, "span": {"begin": 1643, "end": 1651}}, {"id": ["mim:114550", "mesh:D006528"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "HCC", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9994542002677917, "span": {"begin": 1712, "end": 1715}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "patient", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9726518988609314, "span": {"begin": 1729, "end": 1736}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009369"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "tumor", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999257326126099, "span": {"begin": 1877, "end": 1882}}], "text": "A mutation in codon 249 in the human p53 gene is observed up to 50% of liver cancers in Qidong, China (Hsu et al., Nature 350: 427-428, 1991) and in Mozambique, areas with high exposure to AFB1. A G:C to T:A transversion in the third base of codon 249 in p53 is observed in up to 75% of HCC in high-incidence areas of China and East Africa (Gouas et al., 2009). This specific mutation is very rare in HCC from no or low aflatoxin areas (Hsu et al., 1991 and Bressac et al. Nature, 350:429-431, 1991). This mutation is also very rare in other types of tumors (Gouas et al., 2009).  Evidence for temporality for mutation and HCC The Dycaico et al. (1996) Big Blue&trade; rat study and the Chen et al. Big Blue&trade; neonatal mouse study (2010) show that AFB1 can induce mutation (in a surrogate gene) following a relatively short in vivo exposure time.  The codon 249 mutation is detectable in exposed tissues ahead of cancer development (Gouas et al., Cancer Letters, 286: 29-37, 2009)  In a review of p53 mutation at codon 249 (R249S), Gouas et al., 2009 report that cancer patients have significantly higher levels of DNA fragments circulating in their blood than healthy individuals. Using restriction digestion methods (RFLP-PCR) R249S has been detected in patients from The Gambia, and this was strongly associated with HCC. The presence of this mutation in plasma was linked to the codon 249 p53 mutation in the tumors of individual patients. In addition, using a sensitive and quantitative mass spectrometric method, combined with other molecular techniques, Jackson et al., 2003 were able to detect the R249S mutation in the plasma of patients from The Gambia both before and after clinical diagnosis of HCC (in the same patient) (Jackson et al., 2003). These data provide good evidence of an appropriate temporal sequence of events: induction of the mutation precedes tumor formation.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:40:15 +0000 2026"}